<exercise id="eip-200" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="eip-35">
<para id="eip-id2640726"> <title>Unreasonable Results</title></para>
   <para id="eip-id1767627"> (a) What is the final speed of an electron accelerated from rest through a voltage of 25.0 MV by a negatively charged Van de Graaff terminal?</para>
<para id="eip-id2057005">(b) What is unreasonable about this result? </para>
<para id="eip-id2899769">(c) Which assumptions are responsible?</para>

</problem>

<solution id="eip-647">
<para id="eip-id1598912">(a)  <m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>2.96</m:mn><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mn>10</m:mn><m:mn>9</m:mn></m:msup><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>m/s</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:math></para><para id="eip-id1305472">(b) This velocity is far too great. It is faster than the speed of light.</para>
<para id="eip-id2223518">(c) The assumption that the speed of the electron is far less than that of light and that the problem does not require a relativistic treatment produces an answer greater than the speed of light. </para>
</solution>
